  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-worstcase",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model reliably identifies worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump",
      "description": "This claim asserts that the CFD hemolysis model, employing the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation formulation with SST k-omega turbulence closure, is sufficient to rank-order hemolysis outcomes across the five specified flow-speed operating points and to identify the worst-case condition with respect to the relative hemolysis index (RH). The claim is grounded in an extensive body of supporting work: mesh independence studies conducted across three refinement levels (coarse 2.1M, medium 4.8M, fine 9.7M cells) demonstrate that RH values converge to within 1.2% between medium and fine meshes; time-step sensitivity analysis confirms temporal discretization error below 0.8% for all operating points; and solver residual monitoring shows six-order-of-magnitude convergence for continuity and momentum equations in all steady-state runs. Boundary conditions were derived from in vitro measurements on the physical pump prototype operated at matched Reynolds and flow-coefficient conditions. The blood damage model coefficients were calibrated against published Couette viscometer data and validated against three independent in vitro hemolysis datasets reported in peer-reviewed literature. Collectively, this body of computational and experimental work provides strong qualitative assurance that the model is fit for the stated purpose. The claim scope is restricted to rank-ordering among the five specified operating points and does not extend to absolute hemolysis magnitude prediction or to operating regimes outside the tested envelope."
    }
  ],
